<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-256-234  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 256 234.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  April 18 1989 v3 n16 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>32-bit color to blaze bright at NCGA show. (Apple scheduled tounveil a 32-bit QuickDraw at the National Computer GraphicsAssociation show) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Guglielmo, Connie.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   QuickDraw (Computer graphics software) (product enhancement).andO;Topic:     National Computer Graphics AssociationProduct Introduction32-BitGraphics SoftwareColorConferencesProfessional AssociationsTrade Shows.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>32-bit color to blaze bright at NCGA showandM;Philadelphia -- Apple is expected to paint the town red --and green and blue-- when it arrives here this week for the 10th National Computer GraphicsAssociation (NCGA) show.andM;The four-day conference, a showcase for the latest in computer graphicsgadgetry, will play host to Apple's introduction of Jackson Pollock, itslong-awaited implementation of 32-bit QuickDraw (see MacWEEK, April 11).andM;Apple last week said that more than 15 Macintosh developers will announceimmediate support for the new true-color standard, including BarneyscanCorp., Levco, Radius Inc., RasterOps Corp., SuperMac Technology andTektronix.andM;According to Laurie Girand, product manager for QuickDraw at Apple, 32-bitQuickDraw will be included in the next major release of the Macintoshoperating system, as well as in the ROM of all future 68020- and 68030-basedmachines introduced by Apple.andM;The company will display its new color technology on the show floor, where itwill also highlight products from about 20 third-party Mac developers.andM;NCGA will feature products from more than 220 exhibitors and is expected todraw more than 27,000 attendees.andO;</TEXT></DOC>